			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Enchanters&message.id=6193#M6193">6</a> of 14
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 511 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			I hear you Nanyea, but most of the fight has gone out of me at this point.  I've suggested so many ideas over the past few years, to never see a single ounce of feedback on any of them (let alone any implementation of them) is all but heartbreaking.   A lot of the enchanter community, I think, feels the way I do - they've been talking and suggesting for years, and now they just wonder why they bother.<br><br>You say they're not going to magically include Enchanter_01.  That's fine, and there's no reason they should have to.   But they have to put a thumb on the pulse of the community in some way.   We shouldn't -need- a champion to crusade for us.   At most, all we should need is someone to gather ideas and plant them on the doorstep.  Which, incidentally, the top ten list utterly does not do.  The top ten list has been occupied by the same 10 issues for months if not years now.  Either the devs have read it more than once and have an idea of what our issues are, or they've never bothered to look at it and don't have a freaking clue.  That's only half the battle though.   While I respect the creativity of the dev team, a lot of the ideas that come down to us are half-baked "who on earth though this would be useful" sort of things (Virus mez leaps to mind.).  There are tons of ideas circulating throughout the community on useful ways to address charm, mez, utility, and everything under the sun... but no one at Sony ever appears to hear about any of them.<br><br>And then, of course, we have the mez stacking debacle (I can't think of a gentler word); It's almost as though someone at Sony deliberately went forth to -punish- us for complaining about something, because, to be frank, if they had read -any- of my posts on the subject of Wake of Felicity stacking, they would have noticed that I included very precise instructions on how to fix it.  Instead, they've been fooling around with half a dozen different spells and generally leaving the whole system in a shambles.  The only possible alternatives here are that the devs are either impossibly poorly informed (and seemingly unwilling to become better informed) or that they have some sort of policy that requires them to -never- fix a problem in a way suggested by a player.<br><br>And then there is an entirely different issue - people like Bravor, who seem to believe that everything is pretty much fine, and that people who are dying to single adds are obviously screwing up since they have so many resources.  Unfortunately, most of those resources are on long re-use timers, or require the user to live through the casting time.  If we are ever to function as CC anywhere nearly as reliably as a monk or a bard, we need to be able to deal with single adds -guaranteed-, without using any resources that take more than a minute or so to recover.  The likes of Rune of Shadows, Mind Over Matter, and Color Shock should be reserved for pulls of more than two.  It's the "I don't want the game to be too easy! Please don't improve my class!"  faction that, in my opinion, has a difficult time discerning between "hard" and "random" and which sends mixed and confused messages to the dev team.<br><br>So. To sum up.  I sortof agree with you, and I wouldn't even -mind- stepping forward to trying to make something happen.  I applied to the class correspondant post, but apparently only enchanters from Anguish+ guilds are considered for that sort of thing.   But I resent the implication that I, or, indeed, the community as a whole, have in any way rolled over and accepted what has been handed to us.  Certainly, we haven't trashed and railed and foamed at the mouth - in part because we are better that that, as a whole, and in part because we recognize that it doesn't really accomplish anything.   We've tried our best to be constructive, to offer useful suggestions, and to point out problems, but this effort has, as best anyone can tell, fallen on ears that either deaf or too busy working on the next expansion to do anything.<br><br>I'm not going to sidetrack this thread by talking about charm, or proposed solutions for it, or anything of the sort;  I'm just going to say that the devs need to show more honest interest in the ideas of the community if the community is to feel that there is a point in offering said suggestions.  And I think I'm a pretty moderate voice on this subject.  I'm not in the "You all suck because you can't hack it" camp, nor am I in the "Sony doesn't know what do with us! They're trying to eliminate our class! They hate us! And they're stupid and ugly and smell bad!" camp either. (Don't believe me? Go read a post by Mutantman. =/ )<p>Message Edited by Unmei on <span class=date_text>01-05-2006</span> <span class=time_text>11:33 AM</span>	
		</td></tr>
